# 3. Project Structure (Recommended)

src/
 ├── main.tsx
 ├── App.tsx
 ├── routes/
 │    ├── Dashboard.tsx
 │    ├── Orders.tsx
 │    └── Login.tsx
 ├── features/
 │    ├── orders/
 │    ├── users/
 │    └── shared/
 ├── components/
 ├── graphql/
 ├── hooks/
 ├── utils/
 ├── test-utils/
 └── styles/

Principles:
- Feature-based grouping preferred over type-based grouping.
- Mirror backend domain boundaries where possible.
- Avoid deep cross-feature imports.

---

# 4. Build & Artifact Model

## 4.1 Build Command

npm run build

Produces:

dist/
 ├── index.html
 ├── assets/
 │    ├── main.[hash].js
 │    ├── vendor.[hash].js
 │    └── route-chunks.[hash].js

## 4.2 Code Splitting

- Use route-based lazy loading.
- Dynamic imports for heavy modules.
- Prevent monolithic bundles.

Example pattern:

const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./routes/Dashboard'))

---

# 5. S3 Hosting Configuration

## 5.1 S3 Bucket Rules

- Static website hosting enabled
- Public access blocked
- Access via CloudFront only
- Versioning enabled (recommended)

## 5.2 Folder Upload

Upload entire dist/ directory to S3 bucket root.

---

# 6. CloudFront Configuration

## 6.1 Origin

- Origin: S3 bucket
- Restrict direct S3 access using Origin Access Control (OAC)

## 6.2 Routing Behavior (Critical for SPA)

All unknown routes must return index.html.

Error handling configuration:
- 403 → /index.html
- 404 → /index.html

This prevents deep-link refresh failures.

## 6.3 Caching Strategy

- index.html → low cache TTL
- JS/CSS assets → long cache TTL (hash-based invalidation)
- Enable compression (gzip/brotli)

---

# 7. API Communication Architecture

## 7.1 Base URL Strategy

Do NOT hardcode API URLs.

Use environment-based configuration:
- VITE_API_URL (or equivalent)

Examples:
- Development: http://localhost:8080/graphql
- Production: https://api.yourdomain.com/graphql

## 7.2 CORS Configuration (Backend Responsibility)

Backend must allow:
- Origin: app.yourdomain.com
- Credentials if required

Frontend must never bypass CORS via proxy hacks in production.

---

# 8. Environment Configuration Model

## 8.1 Environment Separation

- .env.development
- .env.production

Only public-safe variables allowed in frontend.

Never store:
- Secrets
- API keys (unless public)
- Private tokens

---

# 9. Security Model

1. All traffic over HTTPS (CloudFront TLS)
2. Content Security Policy headers (recommended via CloudFront)
3. No secrets in SPA code
4. Authentication tokens stored securely (HTTP-only cookies preferred)

---

# 10. Observability & Monitoring

## 10.1 Frontend Monitoring

Recommended:
- Real User Monitoring (RUM)
- Error tracking (e.g., Sentry)

## 10.2 Logging Boundaries

Frontend logs:
- User interaction errors
- Network failures

Backend logs:
- Business logic
- Persistence
- Security events

Clear separation required.

---

# 11. Deployment Flow

1. Build SPA (CI or local build)
2. Upload dist/ to S3
3. Invalidate CloudFront cache (if required)
4. Smoke test:
   - Direct deep link (e.g., /dashboard)
   - API connectivity
   - Authentication flow

Frontend deployment must not require backend redeploy.

---

# 12. Scalability Model

Frontend:
- Infinite horizontal scaling via CDN
- No runtime compute required

Backend:
- Scales independently (ECS/EC2/EKS/etc.)

This separation prevents frontend traffic from impacting backend compute.

---

# 13. Failure Modes & Guardrails

Common mistakes (Forbidden):

- Hosting SPA inside Spring Boot
- Path-based API routing under same domain without planning
- Hardcoded API URLs
- Missing SPA fallback routing
- Large un-split JS bundles
- Storing secrets in frontend
- UI components that only support light mode (missing `dark:` variants)
- Hardcoded color values that ignore the active theme

---

# 14. Future Extensibility

If SEO becomes required later:
- Introduce marketing site separately
- Do NOT retrofit SSR into core app without strong justification

Keep application SPA isolated and focused.

---

# 15. Final Architectural Decision

Frontend Model:
- Pure SPA
- Static build
- Hosted via S3
- Distributed via CloudFront
- Separate subdomain
- Independent deployment lifecycle

This architecture maximizes:
- Maintainability
- Clear ownership boundaries
- Operational simplicity
- Scalable delivery
- Clean testing separation

